JAVASCRIPT LEARNING
1. Difference Between var, let and const
Scope	Redeclare	Reassign	Hoisted	Binds this
var	   No	      Yes	        Yes	    Yes	Yes
let	   Yes	     No	        Yes	    No	No
const	 Yes	     No	        No	    No	No

2. JS OBJECT METHOD  
  const person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  id: 5566,
  fullName: function() {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
  }
};

3.You must use person[x] in the loop.
person.x will not work (Because x is the loop variable).

4.OBJECT ENTRIES 
const fruits = {Bananas:300, Oranges:200, Apples:500};

let text = "";
for (let [fruit, value] of Object.entries(fruits)) {
  text += fruit + ": " + value + "<br>";
}

5.Object.values() creates an array from the property values: 
Const myArray = Object.values(fruits);
answer = 300,200,500

6. JSON.STRINGIFY 
Using JSON.stringify()
JavaScript objects can be converted to a string with JSON method JSON.stringify().
JSON.stringify() is included in JavaScript and supported in all major browsers.
Note:
The result will be a string written in JSON notation:
{"name":"John","age":50,"city":"New York"}

7.You can NOT add a new property to an object constructor.

8.To add a new property, you must add it to the constructor function prototype:
Example
Person.prototype.nationality = "English";

9.Built-in JavaScript Constructors
JavaScript has built-in constructors for all native objects:

new Object()   // A new Object object
new Array()    // A new Array object
new Map()      // A new Map object
new Set()      // A new Set object
new Date()     // A new Date object
new RegExp()   // A new RegExp object
new Function() // A new Function object

10.Use object literals {} instead of new Object().
Use array literals [] instead of new Array().
Use pattern literals /()/ instead of new RegExp().
Use function expressions () {} instead of new Function().

